@TimWhiting The main issue I have with this approach is the lack of robustness. A big driver here is the need for the reliability of builders, in a succinct form. The magic id, and the ability to clash on lifecycle, both create new vectors for bugs to occur, and I would continue to recommend to my team they use builders, as despite being pretty nasty to read, at least we know that they are 100% bug-free.

Regarding examples, I still think the perfect example is simply using a AnimationController, with a duration value tied to the widget. Keeps it simple and familiar. There is no need to get more esoteric than that, it's a perfect little use-case for re-usable boilerplate, it needs lifecycle hooks, and all solutions could easily be judged by their ability to use several animations succinctly. 

Everything else is just a variation of this same use 'Stateful Controller' use case. I want to do X in initState, and Y in dispose state, and update Z when my dependencies change. It doesn't matter what X, Y and Z are.

I wonder if @rrousselGit could provide some insight here, or has any data on which hooks are currently most used. I'm guessing it's 80% Stream and Animations, but it would be nice to actually know what people are using most.

Regarding rebuilding portions of the tree, builders are naturally suited to this task anyways, we should just let them do it. A stateful controller can easily be hooked into stateless renderers anyways if that is what you want (hello every Transition class). 

Just like we might do:
```
var anim = get AnimationController();
return Column(
  _someExpensiveBuildMethod(),
  FadeTransition(opacity: anim, child: ...)
)
```
We could always do:
```
var foo = get ComplicatedThingController();
return Column(
  _someExpensiveBuildMethod(),
  ComplicatedThing(controller: foo, child: ...)
)
```

I think there is definitely an opportunity to improve the naming conventions and make them more flutter like. 

Things like UseMemoized and UseEffect sound quite foreign, and it sounds like we want some way to not have to run the init() code in the build fxn.  

Currently initializing with hooks is like this (I think?): 
```
Widget build(){
   useEffect(
      (){
          // Do init stuff
         return (){  //Do dispose stuff };
      }, [ ] ) //<-- pass an empty list of rebuild triggers, so this can only fire once. Passing null here would let it fire every time.
   );
}
```
I appreciate the brevity of this code, but it's certainly far less than ideal from a readability and "self documenting code" standpoint. There's a lot of implicit magic going on here. Ideally we have something that is explicit about it's init/dispose hooks, and doesn't force itself into build when used with a Stateless Widget. 

Things like useMemoized and useEffect could maybe be better named more explicitly  `hook ComputedValue()` and `hook  SideEffect()`
```
Widget build(BuildContext context){
   List<int> volumes = hook ComputedValue(
        execute: ()=>_getVolumeFromAudioSamples(widget.bytes), 
        dependencies: [ widget.bytes ]);

   hook SideEffect(
       execute: ()=>_recordSongChangedAnalytics()
       dependencies: [ widget.songUrl ]);
   )

   return SongVisualizer(volumes: volumes);
}
```

Opinion: The community inclination to name hooks as the de-facto solution to this problem roots from a bias for functions. Functions are simpler to compose than objects, especially in a statically-typed language. I think the mental model of Widgets for many developers is effectively just the `build` method.

I think if you frame the problem in terms of the basics, you're more likely to design a solution that works well in the rest of the library.

As for the `hook` keyword in terms of the basics; one could look at it as both declaring and defining a function from some kind of template (a macro), and the `hook` prefix is really just calling out that the built-function has internal state (c-style statics.)

I wonder if there isn't some kind of prior-art in Swift FunctionBuilders.

While we're dreaming, I'll clarify my guess at what would be the necessary code:

```dart
Hook SideEffect(void Function() execute, List<Object> dependencies) {
  // Whatever happens each build.
}

Widget build(BuildContext context){
   List<int> volumes = hook ComputedValue(
        execute: ()=>_getVolumeFromAudioSamples(widget.bytes), 
        dependencies: [ widget.bytes ]);

   SideEffect(
       execute: ()=>_recordSongChangedAnalytics()
       dependencies: [ widget.songUrl ]);
   )

   return SongVisualizer(volumes: volumes);
}
```

Where `Hook` is a type-system level hack that helps statically analyze that the resulting hook was called in accordance with what hook-familiar developers know as hook laws. As that kind of a thing, the Hook-type can be documented as something that's a lot like a function, but has static internal mutable state.

I cringe a bit as I write this because it's such an oddity from a language perspective. Then again, Dart is the language born for writing user interfaces. If this kind of an oddity should exist anywhere, perhaps this is the place. Just not this oddity in particular.

Working with stateful widgets is really painfull in Flutter. Everytime i add a state, i have to transform my widget to a statefullWidget, if later i decide to remove it, i have to recreate my stateless widget.

Otherwise, I often have to split my code between declaration, initState, debug and dispose. there is no way to extract the state and its logic together. 

An example would be: The state and the logic of a Multiselect. If i can extract it, i could use the same code for all my multiCheckboxes, multiSelects ...etc.  I write it and test it once and reuse it everywhere. The same applies for Modals, animations, keyboard interactions, FieldControllers ..etc

Many packages try to solve this issue but they are creating others (flutter_hooks, GetX). i avoid to use them because i don't want to rely on them for something so central as the widget lifecycle.

The community is trying hard to reduce the Flutter boilerplate and the lack of state reusability but the core team seem not concerned much about this. 

in React, SwiftUI, Maui every state is one line of code. it's easy to write, read and maintain.

SwiftUI
--

```
struct PlayerView: View {
    var episode: Episode
    @State private var isPlaying: Bool = false

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text(episode.title)
            Text(episode.showTitle)
            PlayButton(isPlaying: $isPlaying)
        }
    }
}
```

React typescript
--
```
interface Props {
    episode: Episode;
}

const PlayerView: React.FC<Props> = ({episode}) => {
    const [isPlaying, setIsPlaying] = React.useState<boolean>(false);

    return <div>
        <p>{episode.title}</p>
        <p>{episode.showTime}</p>
        <PlayButton isPlaying={isPlaying} />
    </div>
};
```

Flutter
--
```
class PlayerView extends StatefulWidget {
  final Episode episode;

  const PlayerView({Key? key, required this.episode}) : super(key: key);

  @override
  _PlayerViewState createState() => _PlayerViewState();
}

class _PlayerViewState extends State<PlayerView> {
  var isPlaying = false;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Column(children: [
      Text(widget.episode.title),
      Text(widget.episode.showTime),
      PlayButton(isPlaying: isPlaying),
    ]);
  }
}
```

### Hooks work in Flutter, and maybe any graphical application.
Below is the simplest form of an interactive graphical application. Almost all of them look this way under the abstractions.
```dart
for (;;) {
  readInput();
  changeState();
  drawState();
}
```
There is still a great fondness for this way of writing GUIs, as made evident by the pervasive use of [imgui](https://github.com/ocornut/imgui) in rendering-enthusiast groups like game-engine authors. **It is simply the best way of getting things done quickly.** (The feature is done fast, and the feature runs fast on the machine)

Our problem with this is that we're running as fast as that `for` loop. We only need to work as fast as a user can create events for us to process, any extra work is wasteful. Especially when the device is battery-powered.

When people talk "state management" they only do so by that name in these reactive GUI frameworks. They do that because state management is just the work required to get our business logic on-screen in it's most up-to-date form **without hogging the system resources.**

**So how do hooks fit into this? Incidentally, hooks are choosing to avoid "state management" as part of the framework. Hooks are an escape-hatch into immediate-mode graphics from within a Reactive UI framework.** Consider [Rules of Hooks](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-rules.html), it is not a coincidence that hooks should always be called each render. This one assumption (abstraction) allows us to think of individual components as their own immediate-mode applications!

The following Widget...
```dart
bool shouldCallAgain;

Widget build(BuildContext context) {
  final request = useMemoized(() => makeNetworkRequest, [shouldCallAgain]); // the dependencies array is state-management
  final snapshot = useFuture(request);

  return Text(snapshot.hasData ? "Cool!" : "Crap!");
}
```

...is a more compact way to model the following immediate-mode code...

```dart
bool shouldCallAgain = true; // The first render should start a request.

for (;;) {
  shouldCallAgain = shouldCallAgain && readInput(); // only check if the user wants a request if one isn't running.
  
  var snapshot;
  if (shouldCallAgain) {
    snapshot = AsyncSnapshot.waiting(makeNetworkRequest()); // pretend this works out asynchronously
    shouldCallAgain = false; // <-------------------------------------- Here's the "state management"
  }

  renderText(snapshot.hasData ? "Cool!" : "Crap!");
}
```

... if we take that immediate-mode code, and define our hooks back in, you'll see that the render-loop is now identical to the `build` method in the `Widget` example.

```dart
List<dynamic> _requestDependencies;
dynamic _cachedRequest;
dynamic useMemoized(dynamic Function() buildValue, List<dynamic> dependencies) {
  if (_requestDependencies notDeeplyEqual dependencies) {
    _requestDependencies = dependencies;
    _cachedRequest = buildValue()
  }
  return _request;
}

bool shouldCallAgain;

for (;;) {
  final request = useMemoized(() => makeNetworkRequest, [shouldCallAgain]); // the dependencies array is state-management
  final snapshot = useFuture(request);

  renderText(snapshot.hasData ? "Cool!" : "Crap!");
}
```
**TL;DR:** My argument is effectively that hooks at least work in Flutter because they appear to be a fine way to organize an immediate-mode application, while proving capable of respecting power-constrained platforms. Being a fine way to structure immediate-mode apps is valuable because they are the common denominator, perhaps as simple as it gets. (Granted, that doesn't make using hooks simple.)

Does Flutter need to do anything to support "hooks" beyond making sure the `build` method is called?

By way of example, here is the code I would love to write, but it really does require some sort of Builder-unrolling, so we can piggyback on the existing Widgets Flutter provides:
```
void build(BuildContext context){
    double opacity = builder TweenAnimationBuilder<double>(duration: 1.second, tween: Tween(begin: 0, end: 0));//
    Offset mousePos = builder MousePosBuilder(); // Light wrapper over MouseRegion
    bool isMouseDown = builder MouseDownBuilder(); // Light wrapper over MouseRegion
    //Do stuff
}
```

Instead, currently, you'd need to write this which is about 30 lines of boilerplate, and it forces us into a Stateful widget which is another 9 lines, which builder unrolling would not. More important than typing lines though, the intent of the class is already getting overwhelmed by boilerplate and nesting.
```
class _MyState extends State<MyView> {

  bool _isMouseOver;
  Offset _mousePos;

  void _handleMouseHover(Offset pos){
    setState(() => _mousePos = pos);
  }

  void _handleMouseEnter(){
    setState(() => _isMouseOver = true);
  }

  void _handleMouseExit(){
    setState(() => _isMouseOver = false);
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return TweenAnimationBuilder<double>(
      tween: Tween(begin: 0, end: 1),
      duration: Duration(seconds: 1),
      builder: (_, value, __){
        return MouseRegion(
          onEnter: (d)=> _handleMouseEnter(),
          onExit: (d)=> _handleMouseExit(),
          onHover: (d)=> _handleMouseHover(d.position),
          child: // Do Stuff,
        );
      }
    );
  }
}
```
I don't think hooks, or vanilla flutter, can do anything like that currently.

I've evolved my StatefulProperties idea into something I think is pretty cool... it plays extremely nicely with Restoration, and allows nesting of arbitrary builders. 

Rather than run from StatefulWidget, this approach leans into them. I don't think the extremely functional approach of React hooks is really where we want to head with Flutter.

Pros:
* Clearly declared fields and initState() call
* Encapsulates arbitrary init/didUpdate/dispose behavior in 'StatefulProperty' objects
* Supports restoration API very nicely
* Minimal boilerplate, no nesting
* Uses classic State/initState metaphor, no "magic" here

Cons: 
* Still more boilerplate than hooks
* Not as composable as hooks, not highly composable at all really... but they can use widgets, which helps a lot.
* Requires a replacement of build, currently `buildStateful` 
* Requires StatefulWidget (but this can also be seen as a plus, as State can be shared, and it's more familiar)
* Not sure how well it will work with DidChangeDependancy/Provider

We could start with usage first. This shows using some complex controller, that is tied into the value of from the widget. It will update internally when `didUpdateWidget` is fired:
```
class _FooViewState extends State<FooView> with StatefulPropertyMixin<FooView> {
  StatefulAnimationController anim1;

  void initState() {
    anim1 = registerProperty(create: (w){
        return StatefulAnimationController(duration: (w as FooView).duration, autoBuild: true));
    }
    anim1.controller.forward();
  }

  Widget statefulBuild(BuildContext context) {
    return Container(
      alignment: Alignment.center,
      color: Colors.black.withOpacity(anim1.controller.value)
    );
  }
}
```

Another example, shows how we could nest some existing builder to give us mouse-coords with minimal boilerplate:
```
class _FooViewState extends State<FooView> with StatefulPropertyMixin<FooView> {
  StatefulMouseRegion mouseRegion;

  void initState() {
    mouseRegion = registerProperty(create: (_) => 
         StatefulMouseRegion(onEnter: (_) => print("Roll over!!")));
  }

  Widget statefulBuild(BuildContext context) {
    return Container(
      alignment: Alignment.center,
      child: Text("${mouseRegion.position}"),
    );
  }
}
```
It works off the idea that if we give the Mixin a `Property builder(Widget w)` for each Property, it can do the rest of the work internally by overriding didUpdateWidget.
```
// This can be run once to create the thing, but also re-run when widget changes, to compare new and old
registerProperty(create: (Widget w) => MyProperty(value: (w as MyWidget).someValue))
``` 

If Widget is ever changed, the Mixin can just run this create builder again, and ask the thing to update it's internal state to match:
```
class StatefulAnimationController extends StatefulProperty<StatefulAnimationController> implements TickerProvider {
  ...
  void didUpdate(StatefulAnimationController newProp) {
    if (duration != newProp.duration) {
      duration = newProp.duration;
      _controller.duration = duration;
    }
    if (vsync != newProp.vsync) {
      vsync = newProp.vsync;
      _controller.resync(vsync);
    }
  ...
}
```
The nice thing is that the Mixin can handle all the `registerForRestoration` calls itself, filling in one of the 2 required methods for `RestorationMixin`. This can be everything from simple values, to complex states. All the implementing view needs to do is provide ids. 

For example, a `StatefulInt`, might exist only to be restored automatically. This allows devs to consolidate all primitives and complex objects in their mind, as a `StatefulProperty`, register them with the StatefulPropertyMixin, and forget about it. 
```
class StatefulInt extends StatefulProperty<StatefulInt> {
  StatefulInt(int defaultValue) {
    _restorableValue = RestorableInt(defaultValue);
  }
  RestorableInt _restorableValue;

  int get value => _restorableValue.value;
  set value(int value) => _restorableValue.value = value;

  @override
  void restoreState(void Function(RestorableProperty<Object> property, String restorationId) register) {
    register(_restorableValue, restoreId);
  }
}
```
Usage, we just need to provide an Id for the view, and another id for the property. Everything else is managed. 
```
class _FooState extends State<Foo> with StatefulPropertyMixin<FooView>, RestorationMixin {
   StatefulInt someInt;
 
  @override
  String get restorationId => "FooView";
  
  void initState() {
    someInt = registerProperty(create: (_) => StatefulInt(0), restoreId: "someInt");
    super.initState();
  }
```
Should be easy to extrapolate that to AnimationControllers, or any other controller. For example, AnimController could save multiple RestorablePrimitives, by suffixing on it's main id, like "anim1-value", "anim1-direction", etc. 

It also supports wrapping of Widgets, and callbacks, this is the full `StatefulMouseRegion` from above: 
```
class StatefulMouseRegion extends StatefulProperty<StatefulMouseRegion> {
  StatefulMouseRegion({this.onHover, this.onEnter, this.onExit});
  final void Function(PointerHoverEvent event) onHover;
  final void Function(PointerEnterEvent event) onEnter;
  final void Function(PointerExitEvent event) onExit;

  Offset _pos = Offset.zero;
  Offset _localPos = Offset.zero;
  bool _isHovered = false;

  Offset get position => _pos;
  Offset get localPosition => _localPos;
  bool get isHovered => _isHovered;

  @override
  Widget addWidgets(Widget child) {
    return MouseRegion(
      onEnter: (m) {
        _updateMouse(isDown: true, position: m.position, localPosition: m.localPosition);
        onEnter?.call(m);
      },
      onExit: (m) {
        _updateMouse(isDown: false, position: m.position, localPosition: m.localPosition);
        onExit?.call(m);
      },
      onHover: (m) {
        _updateMouse(isDown: true, position: m.position, localPosition: m.localPosition);
        onHover?.call(m);
      },
      child: child,
    );
  }

  void _updateMouse({bool isDown, Offset position, Offset localPosition}) {
    _isHovered = isDown;
    _pos = position ?? _pos;
    _localPos = localPosition ?? _localPos;
    setState(() {});
  }
}
```

Best part is, the entire core, is 98 lines! :D

Another cool use case with this technique, you can inline something that is pure events, like a GestureDetector, you don't even need to keep a handle to it, but it keeps it out of the tree. 

Combining Animation, Mouse and Gesture detector, pretty cool demo for about 30 lines, sans comments.
```
class _FooViewState extends State<FooView> with StatefulPropertyManagerMixin<FooView> {
  StatefulAnimationController anim1;
  StatefulMouseRegion mouseRegion;

  void initState() {
    // Controlled animation, auto-disposes and didUpdate with widget deps
    anim1 = initProperty((w) => StatefulAnimationController(duration: widget.duration));
    // mouseRegion to track mouse coordinates
    mouseRegion = initProperty((_) => StatefulMouseRegion(onEnter: (_) => print("Roll over!!")));
    // Gesture detector for entire widget, don't bother keeping a reference, we only care about callbacks here
    initProperty((w) => StatefulGestureDetector(onTap: _handleTap));
    super.initState();
  }

  void _handleTap() => anim1.controller.forward(from: 0);

  Widget statefulBuild(BuildContext context) {
    print("Build!");
    // Border changes color according to mousePos
    double normalizedMouseX = mouseRegion.normalizedPosition.dx;
    Color borderColor = Colors.black.withOpacity(normalizedMouseX);
    // Fill changes color based on animController, which can be controlled via tap.
    Color fillColor = Colors.black.withOpacity(.5 - anim1.controller.value * .5);
    // TextColor changes if mouse is over the application
    Color textColor = mouseRegion.isHovered ? Colors.blue.shade800 : Colors.black;
    // Label shows text position
    String label = "${mouseRegion.position}";
    return Container(
      decoration: BoxDecoration(color: fillColor, border: Border.all(color: borderColor, width: 10)),
      alignment: Alignment.center,
      child: Text("$label", style: TextStyle(color: textColor, fontWeight: FontWeight.bold, fontSize: 22)),
    );
  }
}
```

